<td width=44 valign=bottom style='padding:0in 0in 0in 0in'> <p style='margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0in;text-align:right;'><font size=1>&nbsp;</font></p> </td> </tr> <tr style='height:.05in'>
<td width=70 valign=top style='padding:0in 0in 0in 0in; height:.05in'> <p style='margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0in;'><font size=1>&nbsp;</font></p> </td>
<td width=11 valign=bottom style='padding:0in 0in 0in 0in; height:.05in'> <p style='margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0in;'>&nbsp;<b></b></p> </td>

<td width=44 valign=bottom style='padding:0in 0in 0in 0in'> <p style='margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0in;text-align:right;'><font size=1>&nbsp;</font></p> </td> </tr> <tr>

<td width=44 valign=bottom style='padding:0in 0in 0in 0in'> <p style='margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0in;text-align:right;'><font size=1>&nbsp;</font></p> </td> </tr> <tr>

<td width=44 valign=bottom style='padding:0in 0in 0in 0in'> <p style='margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0in;text-align:right;'><font size=1>&nbsp;</font></p> </td> </tr> <tr>

<td width=44 valign=bottom style='padding:0in 0in 0in 0in'> <p style='margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0in;text-align:right;'><font size=1>&nbsp;</font></p> </td> </tr> <tr style='height:.05in'>

<td width=44 valign=bottom style='padding:0in 0in 0in 0in'> <p style='margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0in;text-align:right;'><font size=1>&nbsp;</font></p> </td> </tr> <tr style='height:.05in'>

<td valign=top style='padding:0in 0in 0in 0in; height:.05in'> <p style='margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-left:8.65pt;text-indent:-8.65pt;'><font size=1>&nbsp;</font></p> </td>

<td width=44 valign=bottom style='padding:0in 0in 0in 0in'> <p style='margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0in;text-align:right;'><font size=1>&nbsp;</font></p> </td> </tr> </table>
<br>

<br><p style='margin-bottom:0pt;text-align:center'><font size=2> 2</font></p><br><HR noshade align=center width="100%" size=2><PAGE>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt;text-align:center; margin-top:16pt;'><b><font SIZE=2>PART I</font></b></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.75in; text-indent:-0.75in; margin-top:12pt;'><b><font SIZE=2>ITEM 1.</font></b><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><b><font size=2><a name="TX247_1">BUSINESS</a></font></b></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><b><font size=2>WEBSITE ACCESS OF REGISTRANT&#146;S REPORTS</font></b></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>A copy of this Annual Report on Form 10-K, along with the Company&#146;s Quarterly Reports on Form 10-Q, Current Reports on Form 8-K and any amendments to the aforementioned filings, is available on the Company&#146;s website free of charge. The Company&#146;s website is www.maac.net and the filings can be found on our Investors&#146; page under SEC Filings. Reference to the Company&#146;s website does not constitute incorporation by reference of the information contained on the site and should not be considered part of this document.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><b><font SIZE=2>THE COMPANY</font></b></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Founded in 1994, Mid-America Apartment Communities, Inc. (the &#147;Company&#148;) is a Memphis, Tennessee-based self-administered and self-managed umbrella partnership real estate investment trust (&#147;REIT&#148;) that focuses on acquiring, constructing, developing, owning and operating apartment communities. Between 1994 and December 31, 2002, the Company increased the number of properties of which it is the sole owner from 22 to 112 properties with 30,666 apartment units, representing an increase of 25,086 apartment units. The Company is also a participant in two joint ventures. BRE/MAAC Associates, LLC (&#147;BRE/MAAC&#148;) is a joint venture with Blackstone Real Estate Acquisitions, LLC (&#147;Blackstone&#148;). BRE/MAAC owned 10 properties, containing 2,793 apartment units at December 31, 2002. Mid-America CH/Realty LP (&#147;CH/Realty&#148;) is a joint venture with Crow Holdings. CH/Realty owned one property with
464 apartment units at December 31, 2002. The Company retains a 33.33% ownership interest in both joint ventures and is paid a management fee of 4% of revenues from the apartment communities owned by the joint ventures. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The Company&#146;s
  business is conducted principally through Mid-America Apartments, L.P. (the
  &#147;Operating Partnership&#148;). The Company is the sole general partner
  of the Operating Partnership, holding 182,462 common units of partnership interest
  (&#147;Common Units&#148;) comprising a 1% general partnership interest in the
  Operating</font> </p>
<p style='margin-bottom:0pt;text-align:center'><font size=2> 3</font></p><br><HR noshade align=center width="100%" size=2><PAGE>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Partnership as of December 31, 2002. The Company&#146;s wholly-owned qualified REIT subsidiary, MAC II of Delaware, Inc., a Delaware corporation, is a limited partner in the Operating Partnership and, as of December 31, 2002, held 15,196,886 Common Units, or 83.29% of all outstanding Common Units.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The Company employed 1,023 full time and 77 part time employees at December 31, 2002.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><b><font SIZE=2>OPERATING PHILOSOPHY</font></b></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><i><font SIZE=2>INVESTMENT FOCUS</font></i><font size=2>. The Company&#146;s primary investment focus is on apartment communities in the Southeastern United States and Texas. Between 1994 and 1997, the Company grew largely through the acquisition and redevelopment of existing apartments. Between 1998 and 2000, its concentration was on development of new apartments. In 1999, the Company established a joint venture and sold assets to that joint venture. Between August 1999 and December 2001, the Company repurchased approximately 1.86 million shares of its common stock, funded in part by asset sales. In 2002, the Company established a second joint venture to acquire new properties. The Company&#146;s present focus is on the acquisition of properties that it believes can be repositioned with appropriate use of capital and its operating management skills. The Company is also interested in increasing its investment in properties in larger and
faster growing markets within its current market area, and intends to do this through acquiring apartment communities with the potential for above average growth and return through investments in joint ventures and in direct purchases. The Company will continue its established process of selling mature assets, and will adapt its investment focus to opportunities and markets. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><i><font SIZE=2>HIGH QUALITY ASSETS</font></i><font size=2>. The Company maintains its assets in excellent condition, believing that continuous maintenance will lead to higher long-run returns on investment. It believes that being recognized by civic and industry trade organizations for the high quality of its properties, landscaping, and property management will lead to higher rents and profitability. The Company sells assets selectively in order to ensure that its portfolio consists only of high quality, well-located assets within its market area.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><i><font SIZE=2>DIVERSIFIED MARKET FOCUS</font></i><font size=2>. The Company focuses on owning, operating, developing, constructing and acquiring apartment communities (the &#147;Communities&#148;) throughout the southeastern United States and Texas in large, medium and small markets. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><i><font SIZE=2>INTENSIVE MANAGEMENT FOCUS</font></i><font size=2>. The Company strongly emphasizes on-site property management. Particular attention is paid to opportunities to increase rents, raise average occupancy rates, and control costs. Property managers and regional managers are given the responsibility for monitoring market trends and the discretion to react to such trends. The Company, as part of its intense management focus, has established a number of training programs to produce highly competent property managers, leasing consultants and service technicians who work on-site at the Communities to generate the highest possible income from the Company&#146;s assets. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><i><font SIZE=2>DECENTRALIZED OPERATIONAL
  STRUCTURE</font></i><font size=2>. The Company operates in a decentralized manner.
  Management believes that its decentralized operating structure capitalizes on
  specific market knowledge, provides greater personal accountability than a centralized
  structure and is beneficial in the acquisition, redevelopment and development
  processes. To support this decentralized operational structure, senior and executive
  management are proactively involved in supporting and reviewing property operations
  through extensive asset management programs and direct on-site visitations.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><b><font SIZE=2>PROACTIVE BALANCE SHEET AND PORTFOLIO MANAGEMENT</font></b></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The Company focuses on maximizing the return on assets and adding to the intrinsic underlying value of each share of the Company&#146;s common stock, routinely reviewing each asset based on its determined value and selling those which no longer fit its investment criteria. The Company constantly evaluates the effectiveness of its capital allocations and makes adjustments to its strategy, including investing in acquisitions and development, debt retirement, and repurchases of shares of the Company&#146;s common stock.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><b><font SIZE=2>STRATEGIES</font></b></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The Company seeks to increase operating cash flow and earnings per share to maximize shareholder value through a balanced strategy of internal and external growth.</font></p>
<br><p style='margin-bottom:0pt;text-align:center'><font size=2> 4</font></p><br><HR noshade align=center width="100%" size=2><PAGE>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><i><font SIZE=2>OPERATING GROWTH STRATEGY</font></i><font size=2>. Management&#146;s goal is to maximize the Company&#146;s return on investment in each Community by increasing rental rates and reducing operating expenses while maintaining high occupancy levels. The Company seeks higher net rental revenues by enhancing and maintaining the competitiveness of the Communities and managing expenses through its system of detailed management reporting and accountability in order to achieve increases in operating cash flow. The steps taken to meet these objectives include: </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.36in; text-indent:-0.36in; margin-top:6pt;'><font size=2><b><font size=2>&#149;</font></b></font><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font size=2>empowering the Company&#146;s property managers to adjust rents in response to local market conditions and to concentrate resident turnover during peak rental demand months;</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.36in; text-indent:-0.36in; margin-top:6pt;'><font size=2><b><font size=2>&#149;</font></b></font><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font size=2>offering new services to residents, including telephone, cable, and internet access, on which the Company generates fee and commission income;</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.36in; text-indent:-0.36in; margin-top:6pt;'><font size=2><b><font size=2>&#149;</font></b></font><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font size=2>implementing programs to control expenses through investment in cost-saving initiatives, such as the installation of individual apartment unit water and utility meters in certain Communities;</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.36in; text-indent:-0.36in; margin-top:6pt;'><font size=2><b><font size=2>&#149;</font></b></font><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font size=2>analyzing individual asset productivity performances to identify best practices and improvement areas;</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.36in; text-indent:-0.36in; margin-top:6pt;'><font size=2><b><font size=2>&#149;</font></b></font><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font size=2>improving the &#147;curb appeal&#148; of the Communities through extensive landscaping and exterior improvements and repositioning Communities from time to time to maintain market leadership positions;</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.36in; text-indent:-0.36in; margin-top:6pt;'><font size=2><b><font size=2>&#149;</font></b></font><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font size=2>compensating employees through performance-based compensation and stock ownership programs; </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.36in; text-indent:-0.36in; margin-top:6pt;'><font size=2><b><font size=2>&#149;</font></b></font><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font size=2>maintaining a hands-on management style and &#147;flat&#148; organizational structure that emphasizes senior management&#146;s continued close contact with the market and employees; </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.36in; text-indent:-0.36in; margin-top:6pt;'><font size=2><b><font size=2>&#149;</font></b></font><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font size=2>selling or exchanging underperforming assets and repurchasing shares of common stock when cost of capital and asset values permit; and</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.36in; text-indent:-0.36in; margin-top:6pt;'><font size=2><b><font size=2>&#149;</font></b></font><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font size=2>allocating additional capital where the investment will generate the highest returns for the Company.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><i><font SIZE=2>JOINT VENTURE STRATEGY</font></i><font size=2>. One of the Company&#146;s strategies is to co-invest with private capital partners in joint venture opportunities which enable it to obtain a higher return on its investment through management fees, which leverages the Company&#146;s recognized skills in acquiring, repositioning, redeveloping and managing multifamily investments. The Company is actively seeking attractively priced opportunities in which it and its joint venture partners can invest. The Company established a joint venture in 1999 with Blackstone and a second joint venture in 2002 with Crow Holdings. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><i><font SIZE=2>DISPOSITION STRATEGY</font></i><font size=2>. The Company is committed to the selective disposition of mature assets, defined as those apartment communities that no longer meet the Company&#146;s investment criteria and long-term strategic objectives. Typically, the Company selects assets for disposition that do not meet its present investment criteria including future return on investment, location, market, potential for growth, and capital needs. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><i><font SIZE=2>ACQUISITION STRATEGY</font></i><font size=2>. One of the Company&#146;s growth strategies is to acquire and redevelop apartment communities that meet its investment criteria and focus as discussed above. The Company has extensive experience and research-based skills in the acquisition and repositioning of multifamily properties. The Company will continue to evaluate opportunities that arise, and will utilize this strategy to increase the share of its assets in faster growing and larger markets in the Southeast and Texas.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>On July 2, 2002, the Company purchased the Preston Hills at Mill Creek apartments, a 464-unit apartment community in Buford, GA, for $33.7 million. The community was bought with the expectation that it would be subsequently transferred to CH/Realty. On November 20, 2002, at the Company&#146;s cost, Preston Hills at Mill Creek was transferred into CH/Realty. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><i><font SIZE=2>DEVELOPMENT STRATEGY</font></i><font size=2>. In late 1997, the Company&#146;s emphasis shifted from acquisitions to development because of its belief that under then-current market conditions, such development would generate higher quality assets and higher long-term investment returns. In 2002, the Company completed a four-year $300 million construction program of high quality apartments in several markets. This represents the completion of the development program initiated in 1997. In 1999, management decided to exit the construction and development business upon completion of the Company&#146;s existing development pipeline after determining that market conditions were changing, making it unlikely that future proposed projects would meet the Company&#146;s profitability targets over the next few years.</font></p>
<br><p style='margin-bottom:0pt;text-align:center'><font size=2> 5</font></p><br><HR noshade align=center width="100%" size=2><PAGE>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>At December 31, 2002, the Company had two completed development properties with 921 apartment units in various stages of lease-up and no properties in development. The Company periodically evaluates opportunities for profitable future development investments.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><b><font SIZE=2>SHARE REPURCHASE PROGRAM</font></b></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>In 1999, the Company&#146;s Board of Directors approved an increase in the number of shares of the Company&#146;s common stock authorized to be repurchased to 4 million shares. As of December 31, 2002 the Company had repurchased a total of approximately 1.86 million shares (8% of the shares of common stock and Common Units outstanding as of the beginning of the repurchase program). From time to time the Company intends to sell assets based on its disposition strategy outlined in this Annual Report and use the proceeds to repurchase shares when it believes that shareholder value is enhanced. Factors affecting this determination include the share price, asset dispositions and pricing, financing agreements and rates of return of alternative investments. No shares were repurchased during 2002.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><b><font SIZE=2>COMPETITION</font></b></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>All of the Company&#146;s Communities are located in areas that include other apartment communities. Occupancy and rental rates are affected by the number of competitive apartment communities in a particular area. The owners of competing apartment communities may have greater resources than the Company, and the managers of these communities may have more experience than the Company&#146;s management. Moreover, single-family rental housing, manufactured housing, condominiums and the new and existing home markets provide housing alternatives to potential residents of apartment communities.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Apartment communities compete on the basis of monthly rent, discounts, and facilities offered such as apartment size and amenities, and apartment community amenities, including recreational facilities, resident services, and physical property condition. The Company makes capital improvements to both the communities and individual apartments on a regular basis in order to maintain a competitive position in each individual market.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><b><font SIZE=2>ENVIRONMENTAL MATTERS</font></b></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>As part of the acquisition process, the Company generally obtains environmental audits on all of its Communities from various outside environmental engineering firms. The purpose of these audits is to identify potential sources of contamination at the Communities and to assess the status of environmental regulatory compliance. These audits generally include historical reviews of the Communities, reviews of certain public records, preliminary investigations of the sites and surrounding properties, visual inspection for the presence of asbestos, PCBs and underground storage tanks and the preparation and issuance of written reports. Depending on the results of these audits, more invasive procedures, such as soil sampling or ground water analysis, will be performed to investigate potential sources of contamination. These audits must be satisfactorily completed before the Company takes ownership of an acquisition property,
however, no assurance can be given that the audits identify all significant environmental problems.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Under various federal, state and local laws and regulations, an owner or operator of real estate may be liable for the costs of removal or remediation of certain hazardous or toxic substances on properties. Such laws often impose such liability without regard to whether the owner caused or knew of the presence of hazardous or toxic substances and whether or not the storage of such substances was in violation of a resident&#146;s lease. Furthermore, the cost of remediation and removal of such substances may be substantial, and the presence of such substances, or the failure to promptly remediate such substances, may adversely affect the owner&#146;s ability to sell such real estate or to borrow using such real estate as collateral.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The Company is aware of environmental concerns specifically relating to potential issues resulting from mold in residential properties and has in place an active management and preventive maintenance program that includes procedures specifically related to mold. The Company has established a policy requiring residents to sign a mold addendum to lease. The Company has also purchased a $2 million insurance policy that covers remediation and exposure to mold. The Company, therefore, believes that its exposure to this issue is limited and controlled.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The environmental
  audit reports received by the Company have not revealed any material environmental
  liability. The Company is not aware of any existing conditions that would currently
  be considered an environmental liability. Nevertheless, it is possible that
  the audit reports do not reveal all environmental </font></p>
<p style='margin-bottom:0pt;text-align:center'><font size=2> 6</font></p><br><HR noshade align=center width="100%" size=2><PAGE>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>liabilities or that there are material environmental liabilities of which the Company is unaware. Moreover, no assurance can be given concerning future laws, ordinances or regulations, or the potential introduction of hazardous or toxic substances by neighboring properties or residents. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The Company believes that its Communities are in compliance in all material respects with all applicable federal, state and local ordinances and regulations regarding hazardous or toxic substances and other environmental matters.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><b><font SIZE=2>RECENT DEVELOPMENTS</font></b></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><i><font SIZE=2>DISTRIBUTION</font></i><font size=2>. In January 2003, the Company announced a quarterly distribution to common shareholders of $.585 per share, paid on January 31, 2003.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><i><font SIZE=2>ACQUISITIONS.</font></i><br><font size=2>On January 20, 2003, CH/Realty acquired The Preserve at Arbor Lakes, a 284-unit apartment community in Jacksonville, FL, for $22.1 million. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>On February 7, 2003, the Company acquired the Green Oaks apartments, a 300-unit apartment community located in Grand Prairie, TX for $18.9 million. The Company plans to transfer the property to CH/Realty once a financing commitment has been received under the provisions of the joint venture&#146;s Freddie Mac credit facility.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><i><font SIZE=2>REFINANCINGS AND DERIVATIVE FINANCIAL INSTRUMENTS.</font></i><font size=2> On March 3, 2003, the Company refinanced $142 million aggregate principal amount of publicly held collateralized bonds using one of the Company&#146;s secured credit facilities with Prudential Mortgage Capital, credit-enhanced by Fannie Mae (the &#147;FNMA Facility&#148;). The maturing bonds had a fixed interest rate of 6.38%. The Company previously entered into 5 forward interest rate swap agreements totaling $175 million that become operative during 2003 in order to manage the interest rate risk on this and other refinancings expected in 2003. The weighted average fixed rate for the forward swaps is 5.21%. On March 3, 2003, the first of these swaps became operative, representing a $25 million notional amount with a 5.50% fixed rate and a termination date of March 3, 2005. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.75in; text-indent:-0.75in; margin-top:12pt;'><b><font SIZE=2>ITEM 2.</font></b><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><b><font size=2><a name="TX247_2">PROPERTIES</a></font></b></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The Company and its joint ventures seek to acquire and develop apartment communities located in the southeastern United States and Texas that are appealing to middle income residents with the potential for above average growth and return on investment. Approximately 72% of the Company&#146;s apartment units are located in Georgia, Florida, Tennessee and Texas markets. The Company&#146;s strategic focus is to provide its residents high quality apartment units in attractive community settings, characterized by extensive landscaping and attention to aesthetic detail. The Company utilizes its experience and expertise in maintenance, landscaping, marketing and management to effectively &#147;reposition&#148; many of the apartment communities it acquires to raise occupancy levels and per unit average rents.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The following table sets forth certain historical information for the Communities the Company owned or maintained an ownership interest in, including the 11 properties containing 3,257 apartment units owned by the Company&#146;s joint ventures, at December 31, 2002:</font></p>

<p style='margin-bottom:0pt;text-align:center'><font size=2> 10</font></p><br><HR noshade align=center width="100%" size=2><PAGE>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.75in; text-indent:-0.75in; margin-top:12pt;'><b><font SIZE=2>ITEM 3.</font></b><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><b><font size=2><a name="TX247_3">LEGAL PROCEEDINGS</a></font></b></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The Company is not presently subject to any material litigation nor, to the Company&#146;s knowledge, is any material litigation threatened against the Company, other than routine litigation arising in the ordinary course of business, some of which is expected to be covered by liability insurance and none of which is expected to have a material adverse effect on the business, financial condition, liquidity or results of operations of the Company.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.75in; text-indent:-0.75in; margin-top:12pt;'><b><font SIZE=2>ITEM 4.</font></b><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><b><font size=2><a name="TX247_4">SUBMISSION OF MATTERS TO A VOTE OF SECURITY HOLDERS</a></font></b></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>None.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt;text-align:center; margin-top:16pt;'><b><font SIZE=2>PART II</font></b></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.75in; text-indent:-0.75in; margin-top:12pt;'><b><font SIZE=2>ITEM 5.</font></b><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><b><font size=2><a name="TX247_5">MARKET FOR REGISTRANT&#146;S COMMON EQUITY AND RELATED STOCKHOLDER MATTERS</a></font></b></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The Company&#146;s common stock has been listed and traded on the New York Stock Exchange (&#147;NYSE&#148;) under the symbol &#147;MAA&#148; since its initial public offering in February 1994. On March 17, 2003, the reported last sale price of the Company&#146;s common stock on the NYSE was $23.89 per share, and there were approximately 1,500 holders of record of the common stock. The Company estimates there are approximately 13,500 beneficial owners of its common stock. The following table sets forth the quarterly high and low sales prices of the Company&#146;s common stock as reported on the NYSE and the dividends declared by the Company with respect to the periods indicated.</font></p>

<br>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The Company&#146;s quarterly dividend rate is currently $0.585 per common share. The Board of Directors reviews and declares the dividend rate quarterly. Actual dividends made by the Company will be affected by a number of factors, including the gross revenues received from the Communities, the operating expenses of the Company, the interest expense incurred on borrowings and unanticipated capital expenditures.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The Company pays a preferential regular distribution on the Series A, Series B, Series C, Series F and Series G Preferred Stock at annual rates of $2.375, $2.21875, $2.34375, $2.3125 and $2.15625 per share, respectively. No distribution may be made on the Company&#146;s common stock unless all accrued distributions have been made with respect to each series of the Company&#146;s preferred stock. No assurance can be given that the Company will be able to maintain its distribution rate on its common stock or make required distributions with respect to the Series A, Series B, Series C, Series F and Series G Preferred Stock. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Future distributions by the Company will be at the discretion of the Board of Directors and will depend on the actual funds available for distribution of the Company, its financial condition, capital requirements, the annual distribution requirements under the REIT provisions of the Internal Revenue Code and such other factors as the Board of Directors deems relevant.</font></p>
<br><p style='margin-bottom:0pt;text-align:center'><font size=2> 11</font></p><br><HR noshade align=center width="100%" size=2><PAGE>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The Company has established
  the Direct Stock Purchase and Distribution Reinvestment Plan (the &#147;DSPDRP&#148;)
  under which holders of common stock (and Series A, Series B, Series C, Series
  F and Series G Preferred Stock) can elect automatically to reinvest their distributions
  in additional shares of common stock and/or to make optional purchases of common
  stock free of brokerage commissions and charges of at least $250, but not more
  than $5,000 in any given month. To fulfill its obligations under the DSPDRP,
  the Company may either issue additional shares of common stock or repurchase
  common stock in the open market. The Company may elect to sell shares under
  the DSPDRP at up to a 5% discount, but did not sell any shares at a discount
  in 2002. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size="2">Information related
  to securities authorized for issuance under equity compensation plans as required
  by paragraph (d)(2) of this Item is incorporated by reference to the Company&#146;s
  definitive proxy statement to be filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.75in; text-indent:-0.75in; margin-top:12pt;'><b><font SIZE=2>ITEM 6.</font></b><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><b><font size=2><a name="TX247_6">SELECTED FINANCIAL DATA</a></font></b></p>

<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:0pt;'><b><font size=2>______________</font></b></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.36in; text-indent:-0.36in; margin-top:3pt;'><font size=2><sup>(1)</sup></font><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font size=2>Total capitalization is total debt and market capitalization of preferred shares (value based on $25 per share liquidation preference),</font><font size=2> </font><font size=2>common shares and partnership units (value based on common stock equivalency).</font></p>

<br><p style='margin-bottom:0pt;text-align:center'><font size=2> 13</font></p><br><HR noshade align=center width="100%" size=2><PAGE>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.75in; text-indent:-0.75in; margin-top:12pt;'><b><font SIZE=2>ITEM 7.</font></b><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><b><font size=2><a name="TX247_7">MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS OF FINANCIAL CONDITION AND RESULTS OF OPERATIONS</a></font></b></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><i><font SIZE=2>RISKS ASSOCIATED WITH FORWARD-LOOKING STATEMENTS</font></i></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>This and other sections
  of this Annual Report contain certain forward-looking statements within the
  meaning of Section 27A of the Securities Act of 1933, as amended, and Section
  21E of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended, which are intended to
  be covered by the safe harbors created thereby. These statements include, but
  are not limited to, statements about anticipated growth rate of revenues and
  expenses, anticipated lease-up (and rental concessions) at development properties,
  planned asset dispositions, disposition pricing, and planned acquisition and
  developments. Although the Company believes that the assumptions underlying
  the forward-looking statements are reasonable, any of the assumptions could
  be inaccurate and, therefore, there can be no assurance that the forward-looking
  statements included in this report on Form 10-K will prove to be accurate. In
  light of the significant uncertainties inherent in the forward-looking statements
  included herein, the inclusion of such information should not be regarded as
  a representation by the Company or any other person that the objectives and
  plans of the Company will be achieved. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size="2">The following are
  risks that the Company believes could cause results to differ from projected
  or forecasted results or could have a material or adverse effect on the Company&#146;s
  business.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><i><font size=2>The Company&#146;s Ability To Make Distributions May Be Adversely Affected By Factors Beyond Its Control</font></i></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The Company&#146;s ability to generate sufficient cash in order to make distributions to its shareholders depends on its ability to generate funds from operations in excess of scheduled principal payments on debt and capital expenditure requirements. Funds from operations and the value of the Company&#146;s properties may be less because of factors which are beyond the Company&#146;s control. Such events or conditions could include:</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.36in; text-indent:-0.36in; margin-top:6pt;'><font size=2><b><font size=2>&#149;</font></b></font><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font size=2>competition from other apartment communities;</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.36in; text-indent:-0.36in; margin-top:6pt;'><font size=2><b><font size=2>&#149;</font></b></font><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font size=2>overbuilding of new apartment units or oversupply of available apartment units in the Company&#146;s markets, which might adversely affect apartment occupancy or rental rates and/or require rent concessions in order to lease apartment units;</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.36in; text-indent:-0.36in; margin-top:6pt;'><font size=2><b><font size=2>&#149;</font></b></font><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font size=2>increases in operating costs (including real estate taxes and insurance premiums) due to inflation and other factors, which may not be offset by increased rents;</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.36in; text-indent:-0.36in; margin-top:6pt;'><font size=2><b><font size=2>&#149;</font></b></font><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font size=2>the Company&#146;s inability to rent apartments on favorable economic terms;</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.36in; text-indent:-0.36in; margin-top:6pt;'><font size=2><b><font size=2>&#149;</font></b></font><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font size=2>changes in governmental regulations and the related costs of compliance;</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.36in; text-indent:-0.36in; margin-top:6pt;'><font size=2><b><font size=2>&#149;</font></b></font><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font size=2>changes in tax laws and housing laws including the enactment of rent control laws or other laws regulating multifamily housing;</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.36in; text-indent:-0.36in; margin-top:6pt;'><font size=2><b><font size=2>&#149;</font></b></font><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font size=2>changes in interest rate levels and the availability of financing, which could lead renters to purchase homes (if interest rates drop and home loans are available more readily) or increase the Company&#146;s acquisition and operating costs (if interest rates increase and financing is less readily available);</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.36in; text-indent:-0.36in; margin-top:6pt;'><font size=2><b><font size=2>&#149;</font></b></font><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font size=2>weakness in the overall economy which lowers job growth and the associated demand for apartment housing;</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.36in; text-indent:-0.36in; margin-top:6pt;'><font size=2><b><font size=2>&#149;</font></b></font><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font size=2>decisions relating to the dispositions of assets by the Company&#146;s joint ventures; and</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0.36in; text-indent:-0.36in; margin-top:6pt;'><font size=2><b><font size=2>&#149;</font></b></font><font size=1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font size=2>the relative illiquidity of real estate investments. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Currently, the Company&#146;s
  funds available for distribution are insufficient to fully finance the payment
  of distributions to shareholders at the current rate. While the Company has
  sufficient liquidity to permit distributions at current rates through additional
  borrowings, any significant further deterioration in operations could result
  in the Company&#146;s financial resources to be insufficient to pay distributions
  to shareholders at the current rate, in which event the Company would be required
  to cut the distribution rate. Any decline in the </font></p>
<br><p style='margin-bottom:0pt;text-align:center'><font size=2> 14</font></p><br><HR noshade align=center width="100%" size=2><PAGE>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Company&#146;s funds
  from operations or property values because of these factors which are beyond
  its control could adversely affect the Company&#146;s ability to make distributions
  to its shareholders and could have a material adverse effect on the Company&#146;s stock price.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><i><font size=2>Debt Level and Refinancing Risk May Adversely Affect Financial Condition and Operating Results</font></i></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>At December 31, 2003, the Company had total debt outstanding of $803.7 million. Payments of principal and interest on borrowings may leave the Company with insufficient cash resources to operate the Communities or pay distributions required to be paid in order for the Company to maintain its qualification as a REIT. The Company intends to keep its total debt below 60% of the undepreciated book value of its assets, although the Company&#146;s charter and bylaws do not limit its debt levels. Circumstances may cause the Company to exceed that target from time to time. As of December 31, 2002, the Company&#146;s ratio of debt to undepreciated book value was approximately 53%. The Company&#146;s Board of Directors can modify this policy at any time which could allow the Company to become more highly leveraged and decrease its ability to make distributions to its shareholders. In addition,
the Company must repay its debt upon maturity, and the inability to access debt or equity capital at attractive rates could adversely affect the Company&#146;s financial condition and/or its funds from operations.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><i><font size=2>Variable Interest Rates May Adversely Affect Our Funds from Operations</font></i></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>At December 31, 2002, approximately $298.8 million of the Company&#146;s debt bore interest at a variable rate. In addition, the Company may incur additional debt in the future that also bears interest at variable rates. Variable-rate debt creates higher debt service requirements if market interest rates increase, which would adversely affect the Company&#146;s funds from operations and the amounts available to pay distributions to shareholders. The Company&#146;s $550 million credit facility with Fannie Mae is predominately a floating rate facility, the interest rates on which have been hedged by means of a number of interest rate swaps and caps. Upon the termination of these swaps and caps, the Company will be exposed to the risks of varying interest rates.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><i><font size=2>Increasing Insurance Costs May Negatively Impact Financial Condition</font></i></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Because the Company has substantial real estate holdings, the cost of insuring its properties is a significant item of expense. Due to the events of September 11, 2001 and other recent disasters, premiums for property and casualty insurance have risen significantly in recent months. If the cost of property and casualty insurance continues to rise, its cost of doing business would likely rise, which may in turn negatively impact the Company&#146;s financial condition and results of operations.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><i><font SIZE=2>CRITICAL ACCOUNTING POLICIES AND ESTIMATES</font></i></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The following discussion and analysis of financial condition and results of operations are based upon the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements, and the notes thereto, which have been prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America. The preparation of these consolidated financial statements requires the Company to make a number of estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts and disclosures in the consolidated financial statements. On an ongoing basis, the Company evaluates its estimates and assumptions based upon historical experience and various other factors and circumstances. The Company believes that its estimates and assumptions are reasonable in the circumstances; however, actual results may differ from these estimates and assumptions under different future conditions. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The Company believes that the estimates and assumptions that are most important to the portrayal of its financial condition and results of operations, in that they require the most subjective judgments, form the basis of accounting policies deemed to be most critical. These critical accounting policies include capitalization of expenditures and depreciation of assets, impairment of long-lived assets, including goodwill, and fair value of derivative financial instruments.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><i><font size=2>Capitalization of Expenditures and Depreciation of Assets</font></i></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The Company carries its real estate assets at their depreciated cost. Depreciation is computed on a straight-line basis over the estimated useful lives of the related assets, which range from 8 to 40 years for land improvements and buildings, to 5 years for furniture, fixtures, and equipment, all of which are judgmental determinations. Repairs and maintenance costs are expensed as incurred while significant improvements, renovations, and </font></p>
<br><p style='margin-bottom:0pt;text-align:center'><font size=2> 15</font></p><br><HR noshade align=center width="100%" size=2><PAGE>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>replacements are capitalized. The cost to complete any deferred repairs and maintenance at properties acquired by the Company in order to elevate the condition of the property to the Company&#146;s standards are capitalized as incurred.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><i><font size=2>Impairment of Long-Lived Assets, Including Goodwill</font></i></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The Company accounts for long-lived assets in accordance with the provisions of Statement No. 144, Accounting for the Impairment or Disposal of Long-Lived Assets (Statement 144) and evaluates its goodwill for impairment under Statement No. 142, Goodwill and Other Intangible Assets (Statement 142). The Company evaluates its goodwill for impairment on an annual basis. The Company periodically evaluates its long-lived assets, including its investments in real estate and goodwill, for indicators that would suggest that the carrying amount of the assets may not be recoverable. The judgments regarding the existence of such indicators are based on factors such as operating performance, market conditions, and legal factors. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>To evaluate goodwill and the recovery value of long-lived assets, the Company estimates future operating cash flows and uses these cash flow estimates to determine the asset&#146;s fair value. In the apartment industry the primary method used for determining fair values is to divide annual operating cash flows by an appropriate capitalization rate. The Company determines the appropriate capitalization rate by reviewing the prevailing rates in the Community&#146;s market or submarket.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><i><font size=2>Fair Value of Derivative Financial Instruments</font></i></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The Company utilizes certain derivative financial instruments during the normal course of business to manage, or hedge, the interest rate risk associated with the Company&#146;s variable rate debt or as hedges in anticipation of future debt transactions to manage well-defined interest rate risk associated with the transaction. The valuation of the derivative financial instruments under SFAS No. 133 requires the Company to make estimates and judgments that affect the fair value of the instruments.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>In order for a derivative contract to be designated as a hedge, the relationship between the hedging instrument and the hedged item must be highly effective. The Company performs effectiveness tests using the change in the variable cash flows method at the inception of the hedge and for each reporting period thereafter, through the maturity of the hedge. Any amounts determined to be ineffective are recorded in earnings. The fair value of the hedges are recorded to accumulated other comprehensive income.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>While the Company&#146;s calculation of hedge effectiveness contains some subjective determinations, the historical correlation of the rates of the hedge and the underlying hedged item are measured by the Company before entering into the hedge and have been highly related. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><i><font SIZE=2>OVERVIEW</font></i></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The following is a discussion of the consolidated financial condition and results of operations of the Company for the years ended December 31, 2002, 2001, and 2000. This discussion should be read in conjunction with all of the consolidated financial statements included in this Annual Report on Form 10-K. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>As of December 31, 2002, the total number of apartment units the Company owned or had an ownership interest in, including the 11 properties containing 3,257 apartment units owned by the Company&#146;s joint ventures was 33,923 in 123 Communities, compared to the 33,411 apartment units in 122 Communities owned at December 31, 2001, and the 33,612 apartment units in 124 Communities owned at December 31, 2000. For properties owned 100% by the Company, the average monthly rental per apartment unit, excluding units in lease-up, increased to $661 at December 31, 2002 from $660 at December 31, 2001 and $642 at December 31, 2000. For these same units, overall occupancy at December 31, 2002, 2001 and 2000 was 91.9%, 92.7% and 94.2%, respectively. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><i><font SIZE=2>FUNDS FROM OPERATIONS</font></i></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Funds from operations (&#147;FFO&#148;) represents net income (computed in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America, or &#147;GAAP&#148;) excluding extraordinary items, minority interest in Operating Partnership income, gain or loss on disposition of real estate assets, plus depreciation and amortization related to real estate, and adjustments for the joint ventures to reflect FFO on the same basis. This </font></p>
<br><p style='margin-bottom:0pt;text-align:center'><font size=2> 16</font></p><br><HR noshade align=center width="100%" size=2><PAGE>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>definition of FFO is in accordance with the National Association of Real Estate Investment Trust&#146;s (&#147;NAREIT&#148;) recommended definition.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The Company&#146;s policy is to expense the cost of interior painting, vinyl flooring, and blinds as incurred for stabilized properties. During the stabilization period for acquisition properties, these items are capitalized as part of the total repositioning program of newly acquired properties, and, thus are not deducted in calculating FFO.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>FFO should not be considered as an alternative to net income or any other GAAP measurement of performance, as an indicator of operating performance or as an alternative to cash flow from operating, investing, and financing activities as a measure of liquidity. The Company believes that FFO is helpful in understanding the Company&#146;s results of operations in that such calculation reflects the Company&#146;s ability to support interest payments and general operating expenses before the impact of certain activities such as changes in other assets and accounts payable. The Company&#146;s calculation of FFO may differ from the methodology for calculating FFO utilized by other REITs and, accordingly, may not be comparable to such other REITs. The Company views the amount paid to retire preferred stock in excess of carrying values as experienced in 2002 in relation to the retirement of its Series E Preferred Stock as comparable
to an extraordinary item for FFO purposes.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>FFO decreased during 2002 by approximately $374,000 to $56,838,000 versus $57,212,000 in 2001 and $57,456,000 in 2000, principally because of reduced occupancy and increased concessions at properties owned for more than a year. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Net income decreased during 2002 by approximately $12,557,000 to $16,141,000 versus $28,698,000 in 2001 and $29,787,000 in 2000, principally because 2001 and 2000 experienced net gains of $11,933,000 and $11,587,000, respectively, related to dispositions of assets. In 2002 the Company did not sell any assets. In 2001 and 2000 the Company sold a total of 2,474 units under its disposition strategy, discussed earlier in this Annual Report, and reallocated the majority of the proceeds from those sales to the reduction of debt, the share repurchase program and the completion of development properties.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The following table
  is a reconciliation of FFO to net income for the three years ended December
  31, 2002, 2001 and 2000 (dollars and shares in thousands):</font></p>

<td valign=bottom style='background:#EAF9E8; padding:0in 0in 0in 0in'> <p style='margin-top:2pt;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-left:17.3pt;text-indent:-8.65pt;'><font size=2>Diluted</font></p> </td>

<td colspan=2 valign=bottom style='background:#EAF9E8; padding:0in 0in 0in 0in'> <p style='text-align:right;margin-top:2pt;margin-bottom:0pt;'><font size=2>20,464</font></p> </td>
<td width=14 valign=bottom style='background:#EAF9E8; padding:0in 0in 0in 0in'> <p ><font size=1>&nbsp;</font></p> </td>
<td colspan=2 valign=bottom style='background:#EAF9E8; padding:0in 0in 0in 0in'> <p style='text-align:right;margin-top:2pt;margin-bottom:0pt;'><font size=2>20,551</font></p> </td>
<td width=15 valign=bottom style='background:#EAF9E8;padding: 0in 0in 0in 0in'> <p ><font size=1>&nbsp;</font></p> </td> </tr> </table>
<br>
<br><p style='margin-bottom:0pt;text-align:center'><font size=2> 17</font></p><br><HR noshade align=center width="100%" size=2><PAGE>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><b><font SIZE=2>RESULTS OF OPERATIONS</font></b></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><i><font SIZE=2>COMPARISON OF THE YEAR ENDED DECEMBER 31, 2002 TO THE YEAR ENDED DECEMBER 31, 2001</font></i></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Property revenues for 2002 increased by approximately $967,000 due primarily to increases of (i) $2,707,000 from the development communities and (ii) $1,424,000 from the acquisition of the Preston Hills apartments in 2002 (&#147;2002 Acquisitions&#148;). These increases were partially offset by decreases of (i) $2,104,000 due to the sales of the Advantages and Canyon Creek apartments in 2001 (&#147;2001 Dispositions&#148;), and (ii) $1,060,000 from the communities owned throughout both periods.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Property operating expenses include costs for property personnel, building repairs and maintenance, real estate taxes and insurance, utilities, landscaping and other property related costs. As a percentage of total property revenues, property operating expenses increased to 40.0% in 2002 compared to 38.7% in 2001. Property operating expenses for 2002 increased by approximately $3,336,000 due primarily to increases of (i) $589,000 due to the development communities, (ii) $571,000 due to the 2002 Acquisitions, and (iii) $3,051,000 due to the communities owned throughout both periods. These increases were partially offset by a decrease of $875,000 from the 2001 Dispositions.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Real estate taxes and insurance increased approximately $2,356,000 from 2001 to 2002 due to increases of (i) $1,600,000 due to increased insurance costs associated with the renewal of the Company&#146;s property and casualty insurance and (ii) $756,000 due to increases in real estate taxes.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Depreciation and amortization expense increased by approximately $3,212,000 primarily due to increases of (i) $874,000 due to the development communities, (ii) $374,000 due to the 2002 Acquisitions and (iii) $2,306,000 due to the communities owned throughout both periods. These increases were partially offset by a decrease of $342,000 from the 2001 Dispositions. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>General and administrative expense increased 2.2% or $143,000 as compared to the prior year. Increases in D&amp;O insurance premiums, bank service charges due to the reduction of cash balances held by the Company throughout the year, increased compensation incentives, increased software maintenance expense, and increased legal and director fees due to new regulatory and compliance requirements were partially offset by a decrease in airplane repairs from the prior year and the absence of an airplane lease in 2002 following the purchase of a plane to reduce expenses. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Property management expenses decreased 9.7% or $928,000 as compared to the prior year. The decrease was mainly due to reductions in bonuses and salaries, reduced health insurance costs and reduced franchise and excise taxes from a one-time settlement in 2001.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Interest expense decreased approximately $3,150,000 due primarily to the Company&#146;s ability to take advantage of the decline in interest rates in the second half of 2001 and throughout 2002. The Company&#146;s average borrowing cost at December 31, 2002 was 5.8% as compared to 6.3% on December 31, 2001. The average maturity on the Company&#146;s debt was 10.9 years at December 31, 2002. Amortization of deferred financing costs was $2,712,000 and $2,352,000 for 2002 and 2001, respectively.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>For the year ended December 31, 2002, the Company recorded a net gain on disposition of assets and insurance settlement proceeds totaling $397,000 primarily related to insurance settlements. For the year ended December 31, 2001, the Company recorded a net gain on disposition of assets and insurance settlement proceeds totaling $11,933,000 primarily related to the disposition of two properties during the year. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>In 2002, the Company recorded an extraordinary loss of approximately $1,339,000, net of minority interest, mainly due to the early extinguishment of debt from debt refinancings during the year. In 2001, the Company recorded an extraordinary loss of approximately $1,033,000, net of minority interest, from the early extinguishment of debt related to the property dispositions during the year. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>As a result of the foregoing, income before minority interest and extraordinary items for the year ended December 31, 2002 decreased by $14,331,000 over 2001.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>During 2002 the Company completed the construction of the 244 unit Reserve at Dexter Lake Phase III closing out its development commitments. The Company purchased a 464-unit property in July 2002 which it transferred to its joint venture with Crow Holdings in November of 2002. During 2001 the Company completed </font></p>
<br><p style='margin-bottom:0pt;text-align:center'><font size=2> 18</font></p><br><HR noshade align=center width="100%" size=2><PAGE>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>development of 365 total apartment units in 2 existing communities and sold 2 communities containing 572 total units.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><i><font SIZE=2>COMPARISON OF THE YEAR ENDED DECEMBER 31, 2001 TO THE YEAR ENDED DECEMBER 31, 2000</font></i></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Property revenues for 2001 increased by approximately $5,813,000 due primarily to increases of (i) $7,297,000 from the development communities, (ii) $3,143,000 from the communities owned throughout both periods, and (iii) $1,261,000 from the acquisitions of the Huntington Chase and Indigo Point apartments in 2000 (&#147;2000 Acquisitions&#148;). These increases were partially offset by decreases of (i) $4,394,000 due to the sales of the Pine Trails, MacArthur Ridge, Clearbrook Village, McKellar Woods, Winchester Square, Whispering Oaks, 2000 Wynnton, Riverwind and Hollybrook apartments in 2000 (&#147;2000 Dispositions&#148;), and (ii) $1,494,000 due to the 2001 Dispositions.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Property revenues in 2000 included approximately $787,000 of one-time ancillary income fees from an agreement made with an internet service provider. This agreement was terminated early in 2001.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Property operating expenses include costs for property personnel, building repairs and maintenance, real estate taxes and insurance, utilities, landscaping and other property related costs. As a percentage of total property revenues, property operating expenses remained relatively flat at 38.7% in 2001 compared to 38.3% in 2000. Property operating expenses for 2001 increased by approximately $3,213,000 due primarily to increases of (i) $2,870,000 due to the development communities, (ii) $2,394,000 due to the communities owned throughout both periods, and (iii) $435,000 due to the 2000 Acquisitions. These increases were partially offset by decreases of (i) $1,992,000 from the 2000 Dispositions, and (ii) $494,000 from the 2001 Dispositions.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Depreciation and amortization expense increased by approximately $207,000 primarily due to increases of (i) $971,000 due to the development communities, (ii) $353,000 due to communities owned throughout both periods, and (iii) $288,000 due to the 2000 Acquisitions. These increases were partially offset by decreases of (i) $1,099,000 from the 2000 Dispositions, and (ii) $306,000 from the 2001 Dispositions. Amortization of costs in excess of fair value of net assets (&#147;goodwill&#148;) acquired was $259,000 and $312,000, for 2001 and 2000, respectively, which is included in depreciation and amortization in the accompanying consolidated statements of operations. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>General and administrative
  expense increased 8.4% or $504,000 as compared to the prior year. The most
  significant items contributing to the increase were unusually high airplane
  repair and maintenance costs, which increased $167,000, D&amp;O insurance, which
  increased $110,000 due to increasing premiums, and bank service charges, which
  increased approximately $141,000 due to the reduction of cash balances held
  by the Company throughout the year. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Property management
  expenses increased 8.5% or $753,000 as compared to the prior year. The most
  significant items contributing to the increase were landscape expenses, which
  increased by $306,000 predominantly due to increased vendor charges, and franchise
  and excise taxes, which increased by $261,000 as a result of the settlement
  of disputed prior years&#146; tax assessments.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Interest expense increased approximately $1,862,000 due primarily to the movement of capitalized interest to interest expense as development properties were completed in 2001. This increase was partially offset by the Company&#146;s ability to take advantage of the decline in interest rates in the second half of 2001. The Company&#146;s average borrowing cost at December 31, 2001 was 6.3% as compared to 7.1% on December 31, 2000. The average maturity on the Company&#146;s debt was 10.0 years at December 31, 2001. Amortization of deferred financing costs was $2,352,000 and $2,758,000 for 2001 and 2000, respectively.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>For the year ended December 31, 2001, the Company recorded a net gain on disposition of assets totaling $11,933,000 primarily related to the disposition of the two properties during the year. For the year ended December 31, 2000, the Company recorded a net gain on disposition of assets totaling $11,587,000 primarily related to the disposition of the nine properties during the year of which two were non-taxable exchanges. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>In 2001, the Company recorded an extraordinary loss of approximately $1,033,000, net of minority interest, from the early extinguishment of debt related to the property dispositions during the year. In 2000, the Company </font></p>
<br><p style='margin-bottom:0pt;text-align:center'><font size=2> 19</font></p><br><HR noshade align=center width="100%" size=2><PAGE>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>recorded an extraordinary loss of approximately $204,000, net of minority interest, from the early extinguishment of debt related to the property dispositions during the year. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>As a result of the foregoing, income before minority interest and extraordinary items for the year ended December 31, 2001 decreased by $313,000 over 2000.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>During 2001 the Company completed development of 365 total apartment units in 2 existing communities and sold 2 communities containing 572 total units.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><i><font SIZE=2>TRENDS</font></i></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Property revenues during the year ended December 31, 2002, were impacted by general economic weakness and excess supply of apartments, which was evident throughout the majority of the Company&#146;s portfolio. The decrease in new household formations and single family home purchases due to historically low interest rates have affected demand in many of the Company&#146;s markets, which has created extremely competitive leasing environments. These dynamics are expected to continue for the next several quarters. Current occupancy rates, rent growth, and concession levels are not at historical levels and are not expected to improve until the national economy improves. </font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:12pt;'><i><font SIZE=2>LIQUIDITY AND CAPITAL RESOURCES</font></i></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Net cash flow provided by operating activities remained relatively consistent at $81,076,000 for 2002 compared to $80,577,000 for 2001.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Net cash used in investing
  activities increased during 2002 to $34,182,000 from $13,179,000 in 2001. This
  increase was primarily due to (i) the purchase of Preston Hills in 2002 for
  $33,900,000 whereas in 2001 no acquisitions were made, (ii) in 2002 dispositions
  totaled $36,891,000, including the transfer of a 2/3 interest in Preston Hills
  to CH/Realty for $23,000,000, compared to dispositions of $22,645,000 in 2001,
  and (iii) in 2002, the Company completed $2,270,000 of new construction, compared
  to $16,497,000 in 2001.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The following table summarizes the Company&#146;s remaining communities in various stages of lease-up, as of December 31, 2002:</font></p>

<td valign=bottom style='padding:0in 0in 0in 0in'> <p style='margin-top:2.0pt;margin-left:8.65pt;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-indent:-8.65pt;'><font size=2>Reserve at Dexter Lake III</font></p> </td>
<td width=13 valign=bottom style='padding:0in 0in 0in 0in'> <p style='margin-top:2pt;margin-bottom:0pt;margin-left:-.7pt;'><font size=1>&nbsp;</font></p> </td>

<br>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>The Company&#146;s projections assume that the three properties completed but still under lease-up will substantially stabilize during 2003. At December 31, 2002, 797 of the 921 apartments were leased, and the Company believes that the completion of stabilization of these properties in the second quarter of 2003 is highly likely. The Company does not anticipate that its liquidity will be impacted should these properties fail to stabilize in 2003.</font></p>
<p style=' margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:8pt;'><font size=2>Capital improvements to stabilized properties during the 2002 and 2001 totaled $23,083,000 and $19,365,000, respectively. Actual capital expenditures are summarized below (dollars in thousands):</font></p>

<td width=81 valign=bottom style='padding:0in 0in 0in 0in'> <p style='text-align:right;margin-top:2pt;margin-bottom:0pt;' ><font size=2>19,365</font></p> </td>
<td width=15 valign=bottom style='padding:0in 0in 0in 0in'> <p ><font size=1>&nbsp;</font></p> </td> </tr> <tr>
